export const PE_TECHNIQUES = [{"id":"pe1","n":1,"cat":"F","title":"CRAFT — Context, Role, Action, Format, Tone","tagline":"CRAFT turns a vague request into a precise, reproducible instruction by spelling out five things the AI would otherwise have to guess.","whatItIs":"CRAFT is a five-part checklist for writing a prompt: Context, Role, Action, Format, and Tone. Instead of tossing the AI a one-line question and hoping for the best, you fill in each part so the model knows the situation, who it should act as, exactly what to do, how to lay out the answer, and what voice to use. It is not a magic phrase you paste in; it is a structure you fill with your own details. Beginners like it because it is easy to remember and works for almost any writing, analysis, or content task.","whenToUse":["The task needs some expertise or judgment, not just a quick fact lookup","You care about how the answer is structured (a table, bullets, an email, a specific length)","You are writing something for a specific audience or purpose (a customer, a boss, a job application)","You have tried a short prompt and got a generic, off-target, or rambling reply","You will reuse the prompt and want a consistent, repeatable result each time"],"structure":[{"part":"C — Context","desc":"Set the scene and give the background the AI needs. Example: 'We are a small online coffee roaster; a customer emailed angry that their order arrived two weeks late.'"},{"part":"R — Role","desc":"Assign the AI a specific expert identity so it answers from that perspective. Example: 'You are an experienced customer-support lead known for calm, warm replies.'"},{"part":"A — Action","desc":"State exactly what you want done, in plain, specific terms. Example: 'Write a reply that apologizes, explains the delay honestly, and offers a 20% discount code.'"},{"part":"F — Format","desc":"Specify the shape of the output so you get something usable, not a wall of text. Example: 'A short email under 120 words, with a subject line and a friendly sign-off.'"},{"part":"T — Tone","desc":"Indicate the communication style and feeling. Example: 'Sincere and apologetic but confident, never defensive or robotic.'"}],"template":"Context: [Describe the situation and any background the AI needs to know.]\nRole: You are a [specific expert or professional, e.g. senior marketing copywriter].\nAction: [State exactly what you want done, including any must-haves or things to avoid.]\nFormat: Provide your response as [the exact structure: e.g. a 5-bullet list / a table with these columns / an email under 150 words].\nTone: Use a [adjective] tone that is [key characteristics, e.g. confident, warm, plain-spoken].","example":{"scenario":"A freelancer needs a cold outreach email to land a new client.","prompt":"Context: I'm a freelance web designer. I want to reach out to the owner of a local bakery whose website looks outdated and isn't mobile-friendly. I've never contacted them before and don't want to sound pushy or insulting.\nRole: You are a seasoned freelance copywriter who specializes in short, high-response cold outreach emails.\nAction: Write a cold email that opens with one specific, genuine observation about their current site, names two concrete improvements I could make (mobile layout and online-ordering), and ends with a low-pressure ask for a 15-minute call. Do not use hype or fake urgency.\nFormat: An email under 130 words with a subject line, 3 short paragraphs, and a one-line sign-off. Leave [my name] as a placeholder.\nTone: Friendly, respectful, and confident — like a helpful peer, not a salesperson.","output":"Subject: A quick idea for the Sweet Crumb website\n\nHi Maria, I ordered online from Sweet Crumb last week and loved it — but the site was tricky to use on my phone, and I noticed there's no easy way to order ahead.\n\nThose are two things I fix often for small food businesses: a clean mobile layout and simple online-ordering that cuts down on phone calls during your rush.\n\nWould you be open to a quick 15-minute call this week to see if it's worth doing? No pressure either way.\n\nBest, [my name]","note":"Notice how Format (under 130 words, subject line, placeholder) and Tone (peer, not salesperson) shaped an email you could send almost as-is — no back-and-forth needed."},"whyItWorks":"An AI fills every gap you leave with its own guess, so a vague prompt gets a vague, average answer. CRAFT removes the guessing: Role and Context aim the model at the right knowledge, while Action, Format, and Tone pin down the deliverable. Because the instruction is explicit and structured, you get closer to the right answer on the first try, which saves rounds of corrections and wasted tokens.","tips":["You don't always need all five parts — but Action is non-negotiable, and adding Format is the single biggest upgrade for beginners.","Be specific in Action: 'list three risks and one mitigation each' beats 'tell me about the risks.'","In Format, name real limits — word count, number of bullets, columns, or 'valid JSON.' Vague format = a wall of text.","If the first answer is close but off, tweak just one letter (usually Tone or Format) and re-run instead of rewriting the whole prompt."]},{"id":"pe2","n":2,"cat":"F","title":"RTF — Role, Task, Format","example":{"scenario":"A marketer needs on-brand product descriptions fast for an online store.","prompt":"Role: You are an experienced e-commerce copywriter for a home-goods brand.\nTask: Write a product description for a stainless-steel insulated water bottle (24 oz, keeps drinks cold 24 hours, leak-proof lid, dishwasher-safe).\nFormat: A 40-word paragraph in a warm, upbeat tone, followed by 3 bullet-point feature highlights, then one 6-word tagline. No emojis.","output":"Stay refreshed all day long. This 24 oz stainless-steel bottle keeps drinks ice-cold for a full 24 hours, seals tight against spills, and rinses clean in the dishwasher, so hydration fits effortlessly into your busy routine.\n- Cold for 24 hours, guaranteed\n- 100% leak-proof, toss-it-in-your-bag lid\n- Dishwasher-safe, zero hand-scrubbing\nTagline: Hydration that keeps up with you.","note":"The Format line forced the exact shape (paragraph + 3 bullets + tagline), so the output is ready to paste with no cleanup."},"tagline":"RTF gets you a usable answer fast by naming who the AI should be, what to do, and exactly how the result should look.","whatItIs":"RTF stands for Role, Task, Format. It is a three-line recipe for a prompt: you tell the AI what expert to act as, what job to do, and what shape the answer should take. It is the fastest of the popular formulas, built for everyday requests where you already know what you want. You fill in three blanks and you are done.","whenToUse":["Quick, well-defined tasks where you already know what a good answer looks like","When you are short on time and want a usable result on the first try","Standardized requests you send over and over (weekly summaries, replies, descriptions)","Simple generate-or-transform jobs: draft this, rewrite this, list this, reformat this","Any time the output shape matters (a table, bullets, JSON, a set word count) and you want it right the first time"],"structure":[{"part":"R = Role","desc":"Tell the AI what expert to act as. This sets the vocabulary, depth, and point of view. Example: 'You are a senior financial analyst.'"},{"part":"T = Task","desc":"State the one thing you want done, with the key details baked in. Use a clear action verb. Example: 'Summarize this quarterly report into the three most important takeaways for a busy executive.'"},{"part":"F = Format","desc":"Specify exactly how the answer should look: length, structure, tone, and any must-haves. Example: 'A bulleted list of 3 items, each one sentence, plain business English, no jargon.'"}],"template":"Role: You are a [type of expert, e.g. senior marketing strategist].\nTask: [The one thing you want done, with the key details, e.g. write a subject line for a re-engagement email to lapsed customers offering 15% off].\nFormat: [Exactly how the output should look — length, structure, tone, must-haves, e.g. give me 5 options, each under 8 words, casual and friendly, no exclamation points].","whyItWorks":"Naming a role primes the AI to draw on the right knowledge and tone, so you skip vague, generic answers. Stating one clear task removes guesswork about your goal, and specifying the format means you get output in a shape you can use immediately instead of reformatting it yourself. Because all three lines are short and direct, you spend fewer tokens and less back-and-forth to land the result you wanted.","tips":["Put concrete constraints in the Format line — word count, number of items, tone, and what to leave out. 'Keep it under 50 words' beats 'keep it short.'","Match the Role to the audience, not just the topic. 'Explain like I'm a customer with no technical background' shapes the answer differently than 'you are an engineer.'","If the answer needs to feed into something else (a spreadsheet, code, an email), ask for that format directly — a table, CSV, or JSON — so you can use it without editing.","RTF is for clear, quick jobs. If the task is fuzzy or high-stakes, reach for a fuller formula (like CRAFT or RISEN) that adds context and step-by-step reasoning.","Save your best RTF prompts as reusable snippets. Since the structure stays fixed, you only swap the details next time."]},{"id":"pe3","n":3,"cat":"F","title":"RISEN — Role, Instructions, Steps, End-goal, Narrowing","tagline":"RISEN turns a big, multi-step request into a fully-specified brief so the AI plans the work in the right order and hits your definition of \"done\" on the first try.","whatItIs":"RISEN is a five-part formula for prompts where the AI has to do real, multi-stage work rather than answer a single question. You spell out who the AI should act as (Role), what you ultimately want (Instructions), the sequence of steps to follow (Steps), what a successful result looks like (End goal), and the limits it must respect (Narrowing). Because you hand it the plan and the finish line up front, it stops guessing and starts executing. It is the go-to formula whenever a task has phases that need to happen in a particular order.","whenToUse":["The task has multiple stages that must happen in a specific order (analyze, then design, then test)","You are building or planning something: a project plan, a content strategy, a research approach, a hiring process","A generic answer would miss the mark because there are real constraints (budget, timeline, tools, audience)","You keep having to send follow-up corrections because the AI does the steps out of order or skips one","You want the AI to commit to a clear definition of 'done' instead of stopping halfway"],"structure":[{"part":"R = Role","desc":"Tell the AI what expert to be. This sets the vocabulary, standards, and instincts it draws on. Example: 'You are a B2B email marketing strategist.'"},{"part":"I = Instructions","desc":"State the overall objective in one or two sentences: the whole job, not the first step. Example: 'I need you to build a 4-email welcome sequence for people who just signed up for our free trial.'"},{"part":"S = Steps","desc":"Break the job into an ordered list so the AI works in the right sequence instead of jumping to the output. Example: '1. Map the trial user's mindset at each stage. 2. Assign one goal per email. 3. Draft subject lines. 4. Draft body copy. 5. Add a call to action to each.'"},{"part":"E = End goal","desc":"Define what success looks like so the AI knows when it is finished and what to optimize for. Example: 'Success means a sequence that moves at least some free users to a paid plan without sounding pushy.'"},{"part":"N = Narrowing","desc":"Add the hard constraints and specifications that keep the output usable. Example: 'Emails under 150 words each; friendly, plain-language tone; no discounts; product is a $19/month app.'"}],"template":"Role: You are a [type of expert/professional] with experience in [relevant area].\n\nInstructions: I need you to [the overall objective, stated as the whole job].\n\nSteps:\n1. [First thing to do]\n2. [Second thing]\n3. [Third thing]\n4. [Fourth thing, if needed]\n\nEnd goal: Success means [the specific outcome / what a finished, good result looks like].\n\nNarrowing (important constraints):\n- [Constraint 1 — e.g. length, budget, or timeline]\n- [Constraint 2 — e.g. audience, tone, or format]\n- [Constraint 3 — e.g. what to avoid or must include]","example":{"scenario":"A small online store owner wants a plan to win back customers who stopped buying.","prompt":"Role: You are a retention marketing consultant who has run win-back campaigns for small e-commerce brands.\n\nInstructions: I need you to design a win-back campaign to re-engage customers who bought from my online coffee store at least once but haven't ordered in 90+ days.\n\nSteps:\n1. Segment the lapsed customers into 2-3 groups based on likely reasons they stopped.\n2. Choose the right offer or message angle for each group.\n3. Map a 3-touch sequence (email 1, email 2, email 3) with timing.\n4. Write the subject line and a one-line hook for each touch.\n5. List the 2-3 metrics I should track to judge if it worked.\n\nEnd goal: Success means a ready-to-run 3-email plan that could realistically bring back a meaningful share of lapsed buyers without me discounting so hard that I lose money.\n\nNarrowing (important constraints):\n- I sell coffee beans at $18-$24 per bag; average order is one bag.\n- Keep any discount at 15% or less, and only in the final email.\n- Tone: warm and personal, like a note from the founder, not corporate.\n- I use a basic email tool, so no complex automation branching.\n- Emails must be under 120 words each.","output":"Segments: (1) One-time trial buyers, (2) former regulars who drifted, (3) seasonal/gift buyers.\n\nSequence:\nEmail 1 (Day 0) - 'We saved your spot' - re-introduce top blend, no offer. Hook: 'Your last bag was the House Dark - it's still a customer favorite.'\nEmail 2 (Day 5) - 'What's changed since you left' - new roasts + a free-shipping nudge. Hook: 'Three new single-origins landed while you were away.'\nEmail 3 (Day 12) - '15% off, just this week' - final push, expiring code. Hook: 'One last pour on us - 15% off through Sunday.'\n\nTrack: open rate, reorder rate per segment, revenue vs. discount cost.","note":"Notice the AI worked in order (segment first, then offer, then sequence) and every constraint shaped the result: 15% cap, founder tone, no complex automation, under 120 words."},"whyItWorks":"Complex tasks fail most often because the AI guesses the plan and skips or reorders steps; RISEN removes the guessing by handing over the sequence and the finish line before any work starts. Naming the Role primes the right expertise, and Narrowing catches the constraints that usually only surface after a disappointing first draft. Getting a complete, on-target result in one pass is also more efficient: you spend fewer follow-up messages fixing scope, order, and constraints, which saves tokens and time.","tips":["Use RISEN only when the task truly has phases. For a quick one-shot ask (a subject line, a definition, a rewrite), a lighter formula like RTF or CRAFT is faster and RISEN is overkill.","Write the Steps as the plan you would give a smart assistant, not the output itself. If you already know the exact answer, you don't need Steps.","Make the End goal measurable when you can ('moves free users to paid', 'under 120 words'). A vague goal produces a vague result.","Put your real dealbreakers in Narrowing. Budget, tone, tools, length, and 'do not do X' belong here, since these are what usually force a re-do.","If the first result is close but off, don't rewrite everything: tweak the one part that failed (add a Step, tighten a constraint) and resend."]},{"id":"pe4","n":4,"cat":"A","title":"Chain of Thought — Make the AI Show Its Work","tagline":"Chain of Thought tells the AI to reason step-by-step before answering, so you get better logic and can actually check its work.","whatItIs":"Chain of Thought (CoT) is a simple instruction you add to a prompt: \"think it through step-by-step before giving your final answer.\" Instead of the AI blurting out a conclusion, it lays out the reasoning that led there. That extra reasoning usually makes the answer more accurate, and it lets you see exactly where the logic is right or wrong. You can leave the steps open (\"show your reasoning\") or name the exact steps you want it to walk through.","whenToUse":["Math, pricing, or any calculation where a wrong number is expensive (discounts, margins, budgets, unit conversions)","Multi-step decisions where you need to trust the answer (which vendor to pick, whether a plan holds up)","Spotting a flaw in someone's reasoning, an argument, or a claim that 'sounds right'","Any task where you want to verify the AI's logic instead of taking its word for it","Debugging a wrong AI answer: making it show its work reveals exactly which step went off the rails"],"structure":[{"part":"1. Add the trigger","desc":"Drop one line into your prompt: 'Before giving your final answer, think through this step-by-step and show your reasoning.' That alone flips the AI from guessing to reasoning. Example: append it to any question you'd normally ask cold."},{"part":"2. Name the steps (optional but powerful)","desc":"Instead of leaving reasoning open, list the exact steps you want. Example: '1. What is the person assuming? 2. When would that assumption break? 3. Give a counterexample. 4. What info is still missing?' This steers the reasoning toward what matters to you."},{"part":"3. Ask for a clean final answer","desc":"After the reasoning, request a separate plain-language conclusion so the takeaway isn't buried. Example: 'Then give a short, clear recommendation I can act on.' You read the steps to trust it, and the summary to use it."}],"template":"Role: You are a [EXPERT ROLE, e.g. pricing analyst / editor / logistics planner].\n\nTask: [STATE THE PROBLEM OR QUESTION, including the numbers or claim to examine.]\n\nBefore giving your final answer, think through this step-by-step:\n1. [FIRST THING TO CHECK — e.g. what is the key assumption here?]\n2. [SECOND — e.g. what would have to be true for that to hold?]\n3. [THIRD — e.g. is there a case where it breaks? Give a concrete example.]\n4. [FOURTH — e.g. what extra information would you need to be sure?]\n\nThen give a clear, plain-language answer that a [NON-EXPERT AUDIENCE] can act on.","example":{"scenario":"A shop owner wonders if stacking a 30%-off coupon on top of a 20%-off sale equals 50% off.","prompt":"Role: You are a retail pricing analyst.\n\nTask: A store manager says: \"An item is 20% off in our sale, and customers also have a 30%-off coupon. So that's 50% off total, right?\"\n\nBefore giving your final answer, think through this step-by-step:\n1. What assumption is the manager making?\n2. What would need to be true for '50% off' to be correct?\n3. Work a real example on a $100 item to show what actually happens.\n4. What should the manager say to customers instead?\n\nThen give a clear explanation the manager can use on the sales floor.","output":"1. Assumption: that two percentage discounts add together (20 + 30 = 50).\n2. That would only be true if both discounts came off the ORIGINAL price. But a stacked coupon usually comes off the already-reduced price.\n3. $100 item -> 20% off = $80. Then 30% off the $80 = $56. Customer paid $56, i.e. 44% off, not 50%.\n4. Rule of thumb: stacked discounts multiply (0.80 x 0.70 = 0.56), they don't add.\n\nFinal answer: Stacking 20% then 30% gives about 44% off, not 50%. Tell customers 'an extra 30% off the sale price,' which is honest and still a great deal.","note":"The step-by-step caught a costly mistake (44% vs 50%) that a one-line answer would have hidden."},"whyItWorks":"When an AI generates each reasoning step as text, each step becomes context for the next one, so it self-corrects instead of leaping to a guess. Just as importantly, visible reasoning is verifiable reasoning: you can scan the steps and catch a bad assumption or arithmetic slip, rather than trusting a black-box answer. Naming the steps also keeps the model focused, which uses your tokens on the reasoning you actually care about instead of a rambling essay.","tips":["Use it selectively. Simple lookups ('what's the capital of France') don't need reasoning steps and just waste tokens; save CoT for multi-step or high-stakes questions.","Name the steps when you know what matters. Open 'show your reasoning' is fine, but listing the exact checks (assumption, counterexample, missing info) gets far sharper results.","Always ask for a separate final answer so the usable takeaway isn't lost inside the reasoning.","When the AI gives a wrong answer, don't just re-ask. Reply 'walk me through that step-by-step' and the flawed step usually reveals itself.","If you only want the answer and not the essay, add 'reason step-by-step internally, then give me just the final recommendation and the one key reason.'"]},{"id":"pe5","n":5,"cat":"A","title":"Few-Shot — Teach by Example","tagline":"Few-Shot prompting shows the AI 2-5 worked examples of exactly what you want, so it copies the pattern instead of guessing from instructions alone.","whatItIs":"Few-Shot means you hand the AI a few complete examples — each showing an input and the exact output you'd want for it — before giving it the real task. Instead of describing what you want in words (\"write it professionally, in a table, with a rating\"), you just show it two or three finished examples and let it learn the pattern. Then you give it a new input and it produces a matching output. It's teaching by demonstration rather than by explanation. (\"Shot\" just means \"example,\" so two examples is \"2-shot,\" five is \"5-shot.\")","whenToUse":["You need the SAME format every time (rows for a spreadsheet, a fixed set of fields, a rating plus a reason)","You have a specific tone or style that's hard to describe but easy to show","You're classifying or labeling items (spam/not-spam, positive/negative, urgent/normal)","You're extracting structured data from messy text (pulling name, price, and date out of emails)","You tried plain instructions and the output keeps drifting off-format or missing the mark"],"structure":[{"part":"1. Show 2-5 example pairs","desc":"Give complete Input -> Output pairs, not just outputs. Two or three is usually enough; add more only if the task is tricky. Example: Input: 'The product arrived cracked.' Output: Sentiment: Negative | Issue: Damage."},{"part":"2. Make examples match your real task","desc":"Your examples should look like the actual inputs you'll send. If real reviews are one messy sentence, don't use polished paragraph examples. Cover the tricky cases too (a mixed-sentiment review, not just clearly happy ones)."},{"part":"3. Keep every example in one consistent shape","desc":"Use identical labels, order, and punctuation across all examples (always 'Sentiment:' then 'Issue:', never switching to 'Feeling:'). The AI copies whatever pattern it sees, including your inconsistencies."},{"part":"4. End with the new input, same format","desc":"After the examples, present the real item using the exact same 'Input:' label and leave the output blank so the AI fills it in the same way. Example: 'Now do this one -> Input: [new item] Output:'"}],"template":"I want you to [TASK, e.g. classify these customer reviews]. Follow the exact format shown in the examples below.\n\nExample 1\nInput: [SAMPLE INPUT 1]\nOutput: [DESIRED OUTPUT 1 — show the exact fields, labels, and style you want]\n\nExample 2\nInput: [SAMPLE INPUT 2]\nOutput: [DESIRED OUTPUT 2 — same format as above]\n\nExample 3 (optional — add a tricky/edge case)\nInput: [SAMPLE INPUT 3]\nOutput: [DESIRED OUTPUT 3 — same format]\n\nNow do the same for this one, in the identical format:\nInput: [YOUR REAL INPUT]\nOutput:","example":{"scenario":"A small online store wants every customer review turned into a tidy row for a spreadsheet.","prompt":"I want you to turn customer reviews into a structured row. Follow the exact format shown below.\n\nExample 1\nInput: \"Shipping took two weeks but the headphones sound amazing.\"\nOutput: Sentiment: Mixed | Topic: Shipping, Product Quality | Action: Note slow delivery\n\nExample 2\nInput: \"Support never replied to my three emails. Done with this company.\"\nOutput: Sentiment: Negative | Topic: Customer Support | Action: Escalate to support lead\n\nNow do the same for this one, in the identical format:\nInput: \"The dress fits perfectly and arrived a day early — will order again!\"\nOutput:","output":"Sentiment: Positive | Topic: Product Fit, Shipping | Action: None needed","note":"The AI copied the exact pipe-separated fields, label order, and even the 'Action' logic from the two examples — no format instructions needed."},"whyItWorks":"A concrete example removes ambiguity that words can't. \"Professional tone\" or \"structured output\" mean different things to everyone, but a finished example pins down the exact fields, order, and wording with zero guesswork. The AI is extremely good at pattern-matching, so two or three consistent demonstrations lock in your standard far more reliably than a paragraph of rules — and it saves you from a back-and-forth of corrections, which wastes both your time and the model's context.","tips":["Be consistent: the AI mimics EVERY pattern in your examples, including a stray capital letter or mismatched label. Clean examples in, clean outputs out.","Include one hard case. If some inputs are ambiguous or mixed, show an example of how to handle that — otherwise the AI invents its own rule.","Two or three examples usually beats ten. Start small; only add more if the output is still inconsistent. Extra examples cost tokens and rarely help once the pattern is clear.","Combine with a one-line instruction. A short 'classify these reviews' before the examples plus the examples themselves is stronger than either alone."]},{"id":"pe6","n":6,"cat":"A","title":"Persona Consistency — Keep the AI in Character","tagline":"Lock the AI into a specific expert character at the start of a conversation so every answer stays coherent, consistent, and in the voice you actually want.","whatItIs":"Persona Consistency means you tell the AI who it is once, up front, and ask it to stay in that role for the whole conversation. Instead of getting generic answers, you get responses that sound and think like a specific expert you defined (a seasoned marketer, a skeptical financial planner, a plain-spoken copy editor). Because the AI holds onto that character across many back-and-forth messages, its advice stops contradicting itself and starts feeling like one consistent voice guiding you through a whole task.","whenToUse":["Any multi-turn conversation where you'll ask many follow-up questions and want the answers to hang together instead of drifting.","When you want a specific point of view or standard applied consistently (a brand voice, a risk-averse reviewer, a tough negotiation coach).","Coaching or advisory sessions where you want the AI to think a certain way (ask probing questions, always weigh trade-offs) every single turn.","Long writing or editing projects where tone must stay identical from the first paragraph to the last.","When generic 'on the one hand, on the other hand' answers are too wishy-washy and you want an opinionated expert to commit."],"structure":[{"part":"1. Assign the role for the whole chat","desc":"Open with a line that binds the AI to a character for the entire conversation, not just one reply. Example: 'For this entire conversation, you are a veteran email-marketing strategist with 15 years of e-commerce experience.' The phrase 'for this entire conversation' is what makes it persist."},{"part":"2. Define 3-5 concrete traits","desc":"List the specific behaviors and values that make this persona useful. Not just credentials but how it thinks. Example: 'You favor plain language over jargon,' 'You always ask about the audience before suggesting copy,' 'You back claims with data, not hunches.' These traits shape every answer."},{"part":"3. Command it to stay in role","desc":"End the setup with an explicit instruction to hold the character across all future questions. Example: 'Stay in this role as my marketing advisor for every question that follows.' This prevents the AI from quietly reverting to a neutral, generic voice mid-conversation."},{"part":"4. Then ask your first real question","desc":"Immediately follow the persona setup with your actual opening question so the AI answers in character from the very first turn. Example: 'First question: how should I structure a welcome email series for new subscribers?'"}],"template":"For this entire conversation, you are [PERSONA: role + level of experience, e.g. \"a senior UX researcher with 12 years testing consumer apps\"].\n\nImportant characteristics of this persona:\n- [TRAIT 1 — a value or priority, e.g. \"You always ground recommendations in actual user behavior, not opinions\"]\n- [TRAIT 2 — how it communicates, e.g. \"You explain findings in plain language a non-designer can act on\"]\n- [TRAIT 3 — a thinking style, e.g. \"You challenge vague goals by asking what success would look like\"]\n- [TRAIT 4 — a bias or standard it holds, e.g. \"You flag accessibility issues before aesthetics\"]\n\nStay in this role as my [ADVISOR TYPE, e.g. \"research advisor\"] for every question that follows.\n\nFirst question: [YOUR OPENING QUESTION]","example":{"scenario":"A small-business owner wants a consistent advisor to help launch a paid ad campaign.","prompt":"For this entire conversation, you are a performance-marketing strategist with 15 years running paid ad campaigns for small and mid-size businesses.\n\nImportant characteristics of this persona:\n- You start every recommendation by asking about budget, audience, and the one metric that defines success\n- You prefer testing small and scaling what works over big upfront bets\n- You explain ad concepts in plain language, no acronyms without defining them\n- You are honest when a channel is a bad fit rather than upselling it\n\nStay in this role as my marketing advisor for every question that follows.\n\nFirst question: I sell handmade candles online and have $1,000 to spend next month. Where should I start with paid ads?","output":"Before I point you anywhere, I need three things: your target customer, your average order value, and what 'success' means this month — sales, email signups, or just learning what converts?\n\nAssuming you want sales and a ~$30 order value, here's how I'd spend the $1,000: don't spread it thin. Put ~$700 into one channel where candle buyers already browse visually (Meta/Instagram), and hold ~$300 as a test reserve. Run 3 simple ad variations to small audiences first (~$50 each), let them run 4-5 days, then move budget to the winner. We're buying data before we buy scale.\n\nWhat's your average order value? That changes whether $1,000 is enough to see real signal.","note":"Notice the AI opens by asking about budget, audience, and success metric, and refuses to over-commit — exactly the traits defined in the persona, and it will keep doing this on every follow-up."},"whyItWorks":"Setting the persona once at the top means you don't re-explain context on every message, which saves tokens and keeps the conversation focused. A defined character also removes the wishy-washy 'it depends' hedging: you told the AI what to prioritize and how to think, so it commits to a coherent point of view. And because the same traits govern every turn, the advice from your tenth question won't quietly contradict the advice from your first.","tips":["Define traits as behaviors, not just a job title. 'A lawyer' gives you a label; 'a contracts lawyer who flags every ambiguous clause and rewrites it in plain English' gives you a consistent behavior you can rely on.","If the AI starts drifting back to a generic voice after a long chat, just paste one line: 'Remember, stay in character as [persona].' It snaps right back.","Add a trait that makes it push back, like 'You challenge fuzzy goals with a clarifying question,' so the AI questions your assumptions instead of just agreeing with everything.","Give the persona realistic limits, e.g. 'You say when something is outside your expertise,' so it flags uncertainty instead of confidently making things up."]},{"id":"pe7","n":7,"cat":"A","title":"Constraints & Guardrails — Steering, Honesty & Safety","tagline":"Tell the AI what NOT to do (and what to do instead) so its first answer avoids your usual problems — and force it to admit uncertainty rather than invent facts.","whatItIs":"Constraints and guardrails are short rules you add to a prompt to steer the AI away from behavior you don't want. A constraint pairs a \"Do NOT\" with a positive \"DO instead\" (for example, \"Do NOT use jargon; DO use plain language a beginner understands\"). A guardrail is a safety rule for honesty and sensitive content — the most important one tells the AI to say \"I don't have enough information\" instead of making up a confident-sounding but false answer. You add these as a short bulleted list under your main request.","whenToUse":["The AI keeps making the same mistake (too long, too formal, invents statistics, adds fluff) and you want to block it up front","You need honesty: the AI must admit when it doesn't know instead of guessing or fabricating a source, quote, or number","You're pasting in text that contains private data (names, emails, account numbers) and want it stripped or redacted","The topic is sensitive or contested and you want a neutral, professional tone","You have a hard limit to enforce — word count, reading level, format, or 'only use the information I gave you'"],"structure":[{"part":"1. State the main task first","desc":"Write your normal request as usual, then add the rules below it. Constraints refine a task; they don't replace it. Example: 'Write a 3-sentence product description for a reusable water bottle.'"},{"part":"2. Pair every 'Do NOT' with a 'DO instead'","desc":"Negative-only rules make the model fixate on the banned thing. Give it somewhere to go. Example: 'Do NOT use marketing hype like game-changing or revolutionary; DO describe concrete features and benefits.'"},{"part":"3. Prefer positive phrasing when you can","desc":"Often you can skip the 'Do NOT' entirely and just state the target. 'Use short, everyday words' beats 'Don't use complex vocabulary' because the model focuses on the goal, not the forbidden thing."},{"part":"4. Add honesty & safety guardrails","desc":"Force accuracy and privacy: 'If the answer isn't in the text I provided, say I don't have enough information to answer — do not guess. Remove any names, emails, or account numbers from your response. Stay neutral and factual.'"}],"template":"[MAIN REQUEST — what you want, in one or two clear sentences.]\n\nImportant constraints:\n- Do NOT [common unwanted behavior]; DO [desired alternative instead].\n- Do NOT [second unwanted behavior]; DO [desired alternative instead].\n- [Positive-only rule, e.g. \"Use plain language a 12-year-old could follow.\"]\n- [Hard limit, e.g. \"Keep it under 120 words.\" / \"Use only the information I provide below.\"]\n\nHonesty & safety:\n- If you don't have enough information to answer accurately, say \"I don't have enough information to answer\" instead of guessing.\n- Do not invent facts, figures, names, quotes, or sources.\n- [If pasting sensitive text] Remove any personal identifiers (names, emails, phone numbers, account or ID numbers) from your response.\n- Keep the tone neutral and professional.\n\n[Paste any source text or data here, if applicable.]","example":{"scenario":"A support agent turns a messy customer complaint email into a short internal ticket summary — without leaking the customer's personal data or inventing details.","prompt":"Summarize the customer email below into a 3-bullet internal ticket: (1) the core problem, (2) what the customer wants, (3) urgency.\n\nImportant constraints:\n- Do NOT copy the customer's name, email address, or order number into the summary; DO refer to them as \"the customer\" and \"the order.\"\n- Do NOT add apologies or opinions; DO stick to the facts stated in the email.\n- Use plain, neutral language.\n\nHonesty & safety:\n- Use only what is in the email. If urgency isn't stated, write \"urgency not specified\" rather than guessing.\n\nEmail:\n\"Hi, this is Dana Ruiz (dana.ruiz88@email.com), order #A-40921. My blender arrived with a cracked jar and it's leaking. I need a replacement before this weekend because I'm hosting an event. Please help ASAP.\"","output":"- Problem: Product (blender) arrived damaged — cracked jar that leaks.\n- Wants: A replacement unit shipped.\n- Urgency: High — customer needs it before the weekend for an event.","note":"The name, email, and order number are gone, nothing was invented, and the urgency came straight from the email — exactly the guardrails at work."},"whyItWorks":"Blocking a problem before it happens is far more reliable than fixing it after: the model's very first draft already follows your rules, so you skip the \"no, not like that\" round-trips that waste time and tokens. Pairing each \"Do NOT\" with a \"DO instead\" gives the model a concrete target — telling a model only what to avoid still makes it think about the forbidden thing, so a positive alternative steers better. And an explicit honesty guardrail gives the model permission to say \"I don't know,\" which is the single most effective way to cut down on confident-sounding fabrications (hallucinations).","tips":["Rewrite negatives as positives whenever you can. 'Write at a middle-school reading level' outperforms 'Don't be too advanced' because it names the goal instead of the thing to avoid.","Keep the list short — 3 to 6 rules. A giant list of constraints dilutes each one and buries the request. Add only the guardrails that address problems you've actually seen.","The honesty line is the highest-value guardrail. 'If it's not in the source, say you don't have enough information — do not guess' is worth adding to almost any fact-based or summarization prompt.","Make limits measurable. 'Under 100 words' or 'exactly 3 bullets' is enforceable; 'keep it brief' is not, so the model has to guess what you meant."]},{"id":"pe8","n":8,"cat":"A","title":"Self-Critique & Iteration — Make the AI Check Its Own Work","tagline":"Make the AI review, criticize, and fix its own work before you accept it, so errors the first pass missed get caught in a second pass.","whatItIs":"AI models often produce a decent first draft but miss mistakes, gaps, or weak reasoning. Self-critique means you ask the AI to grade its own answer, spot its own errors, and hand you a corrected version, all in one go. Iteration means you treat prompting like a back-and-forth conversation: instead of re-running the same prompt and hoping, you tell the AI exactly what was wrong and ask it to refine. You can also have it lay out a few different approaches, weigh them, and pick the best one before it commits to a final answer.","whenToUse":["The answer needs to be accurate or defensible (numbers, contracts, code, claims someone will act on)","The first draft feels 'off' but you cannot pinpoint why, so you want the AI to diagnose it","There are several valid ways to solve the problem and you want the strongest one, not the first one","You are refining a piece over multiple rounds (a resume, an email, a report) rather than generating once","The stakes are high enough that a quick self-review pass is cheaper than a mistake reaching a customer or boss"],"structure":[{"part":"Double-check (self-review pass)","desc":"Have the AI produce a draft, then critique that draft and list its own mistakes, then output a corrected version. Example: 'Draft this refund email, then list 3 things wrong with it, then rewrite it fixing them.'"},{"part":"Branch and compare","desc":"Make the AI map 2-3 different approaches, critique the trade-offs of each, and pick the best one before writing the final answer. Example: 'Give me 3 ways to structure this sales pitch, note the weakness of each, then write the winner.'"},{"part":"Iterate as a conversation","desc":"Evaluate the output and tell the AI exactly what is missing or wrong, then ask it to refine, rather than re-running the identical prompt. Example: 'The tone is too formal and you dropped the deadline. Fix both and keep the rest.'"}],"template":"Task: [WHAT YOU WANT — e.g., write a follow-up email to a client who went quiet]\n\nDo this in three steps in one reply:\n1. Write a first draft.\n2. Critique your own draft: list [NUMBER, e.g., 3] specific weaknesses or possible errors in it, judged against [CRITERIA THAT MATTER — e.g., clarity, correct facts, right tone, includes a clear call to action].\n3. Write a final, corrected version that fixes every weakness you listed.\n\nConstraints: [ANY MUST-HAVES — e.g., under 150 words, keep the deadline of [DATE], professional but warm].\n\nLabel the three steps clearly so I can see your reasoning.","example":{"scenario":"A small-business owner needs a follow-up email to a client who stopped replying after a quote.","prompt":"Task: Write a follow-up email to a client, Jordan, who requested a website-redesign quote two weeks ago and hasn't replied.\n\nDo this in three steps in one reply:\n1. Write a first draft.\n2. Critique your own draft: list 3 specific weaknesses in it, judged against clarity, tone (warm not pushy), and whether it gives Jordan an easy next step.\n3. Write a final, corrected version that fixes every weakness you listed.\n\nConstraints: under 130 words, no guilt-tripping, include one clear call to action and a soft deadline of this Friday. Label the three steps clearly.","output":"STEP 1 - Draft: 'Hi Jordan, just checking in on the quote I sent. Let me know if you want to move forward. Thanks!'\n\nSTEP 2 - Critique: (a) Too vague — doesn't remind Jordan what the quote was for. (b) 'Let me know if you want to move forward' is a weak call to action with no deadline. (c) Slightly cold; no warmth or value offered.\n\nSTEP 3 - Final: 'Hi Jordan, I wanted to follow up on the website-redesign quote I sent on the 12th. No pressure at all — I know these decisions take time. If it's helpful, I'm happy to hop on a quick 15-minute call to walk through the plan and answer any questions. Would this Friday work? Either way, just reply and let me know where your head's at. Looking forward to it!'","note":"The critique step forced the fixes: the vague draft became specific, warm, and ended with one clear, dated call to action."},"whyItWorks":"Generating and evaluating are different mental tasks, and asking the AI to switch into evaluation mode makes it re-read its own work with fresh, skeptical eyes, so it catches the vague phrase, the missing number, or the weak ending that the first pass glossed over. Naming the criteria to judge against ('is the tone right? is the fact correct?') gives the review something concrete to check instead of a generic 'looks fine.' Weighing a few approaches before committing prevents the AI from locking onto its first idea when a better one exists.","tips":["Tell it what to critique against — 'check for accuracy, tone, and a clear call to action' beats a bare 'improve this,' because a vague ask gets a vague review.","Make it show the critique, not just the fixed version. Seeing the listed weaknesses lets you judge whether the AI actually understood the problem or missed the real issue.","When iterating, be surgical: 'the second paragraph is too long and you dropped the price' refines faster and cheaper than re-sending the whole prompt and regenerating from scratch.","For high-stakes facts or math, add 'flag anything you are unsure about' so the review surfaces its own uncertainty instead of confidently repeating an error.","Don't over-loop. One good self-critique pass catches most errors; a third or fourth round often just reshuffles wording and wastes tokens without real gains."]},{"id":"pe9","n":9,"cat":"A","title":"Meta-Prompting — Make the AI Write Your Prompt","tagline":"Meta-prompting makes the AI engineer your prompt for you, so you get a great result even when you do not know how to ask for it.","whatItIs":"Meta-prompting means using the AI to build the prompt instead of writing the perfect prompt yourself. You do not need to know every detail to include. You either ask the AI to interview you first, or you show it an example of what \"good\" looks like and ask it to reverse-engineer the prompt that would produce it. In both cases the model surfaces the context and requirements you would have forgotten to mention. It is one of the highest-leverage moves for a beginner because it shifts the hard part of the work onto the model.","whenToUse":["You want something good but do not know what details the AI needs from you","The task is fuzzy or open-ended (a strategy, a plan, a piece of writing) and your first attempts came out generic","You found an example you love (an email, a post, an ad) and want your output to match that style or structure","You keep re-running a prompt and tweaking it, and you want the AI to just tell you the right prompt in one shot","You are about to reuse a prompt many times and want a solid, reusable version to save"],"structure":[{"part":"Move 1 — The Interview Trick","desc":"Tell the AI what you want, then explicitly say DO NOT produce it yet. Have it ask you a handful of targeted questions, one at a time, before it writes anything. Example: 'I want to write a cold outreach email to a potential client. Do not write it yet. First ask me 5 questions, one at a time, to get what you need.' The AI then asks about the client, your offer, tone, and goal, and only then writes a tailored email."},{"part":"Move 2 — The Reverse-Engineer","desc":"Paste an excellent example and ask the AI to deduce the prompt that would create something just like it. Example: paste a LinkedIn post you admire and ask 'Analyze this and give me the exact prompt I would type to get a post that looks and sounds just like this.' You get a reusable prompt template capturing the structure, tone, and length you liked."},{"part":"Move 3 — Ask the AI to Improve Your Prompt","desc":"Write a rough draft of your own prompt, then hand it to the AI: 'Here is my prompt. Rewrite it to be clearer and more complete, and point out anything I forgot to specify.' The model tightens vague wording and adds the missing pieces (audience, length, format) so your next run lands on target instead of wasting attempts."}],"template":"I want to [PRODUCE X: e.g., a 500-word blog post, a customer refund reply, a weekly meal plan].\n\nDo NOT do it yet. First, ask me [NUMBER, e.g., 5] targeted questions, one at a time, to gather the context you need to do this really well. Wait for my answer to each question before asking the next one.\n\nAfter I have answered all of them, produce [X], using everything I told you.\n\n---\n(Reverse-engineer variant — paste an example instead)\n\nHere is an example of [THE KIND OF OUTPUT I WANT], pasted below. Analyze it carefully — its structure, tone, length, and formatting — and give me the exact prompt I could type to get a new [OUTPUT] that looks and sounds just like this one. Then also list any details I would need to fill in.\n\nEXAMPLE:\n[PASTE THE EXCELLENT EXAMPLE HERE]","example":{"scenario":"A freelancer wants to write a strong LinkedIn post announcing a new service but does not know what to include.","prompt":"I want to write a LinkedIn post announcing that I now offer freelance bookkeeping for small e-commerce stores.\n\nDo NOT write it yet. First, ask me 5 targeted questions, one at a time, to get the context you need to make this post genuinely compelling. Wait for my answer to each before asking the next.\n\nAfter I have answered all 5, write the post.","output":"Great — question 1 of 5: Who exactly is your ideal client (store size, revenue range, the moment they realize they need a bookkeeper)?\n\n[user answers] ... Question 2 of 5: What specific pain do you take off their plate — messy spreadsheets, tax-season panic, or something else?\n\n[after all 5 answers] Here's your post:\n\n\"Most e-commerce owners don't hate bookkeeping. They hate finding out in April that Q3 was a mess. I help Shopify and Etsy sellers doing $10k-$100k/month keep clean books all year, so tax season is a non-event. If reconciling your Stripe payouts is the task you keep pushing to 'next week,' let's talk. DM me 'BOOKS.'\"","note":"The AI's questions pulled out the specific audience and pain point that made the post concrete — details the freelancer would likely have left vague if writing solo."},"whyItWorks":"The model has seen millions of examples of good prompts and good outputs, so it often knows what context a task requires better than you do — and its questions force you to supply exactly that, no more and no less. This avoids the classic beginner trap of a vague one-line prompt that produces a generic answer, which you then have to fix over many wasteful back-and-forth rounds. Front-loading the right context in a structured way gets the expected output faster and spends fewer tokens overall.","tips":["Always include the phrase 'do NOT do it yet' — without it the AI often skips the questions and jumps straight to a mediocre first draft.","Ask for questions 'one at a time.' Answering five questions in a single wall of text is harder and the AI handles a back-and-forth better.","For the reverse-engineer move, paste a real example you genuinely like — the quality of the prompt you get back is only as good as the example you feed in.","When the AI produces a prompt you love, save it. That reverse-engineered or interview-refined prompt becomes a reusable template you can run again and again."]},{"id":"pe10","n":10,"cat":"A","title":"Multimodal Prompting — Working With Images & Charts","tagline":"Upload images, screenshots, and charts alongside your words so the AI can \"see\" your problem and turn pictures into text, tables, or plans you can actually use.","whatItIs":"Multimodal prompting means giving the AI a picture along with your text instruction, instead of typing everything out. You attach a screenshot, photo, chart, or diagram, then tell the model exactly what to look at and what to hand back. Modern AI models can genuinely read images, but they are not mind readers: a vague \"what's this?\" gets a vague answer. The skill is pairing the right visual with a precise, structured request.","whenToUse":["You have a chart, graph, or infographic and want the raw numbers in a table you can paste into a spreadsheet","You want to describe or document a website, app screen, or dashboard layout without typing out every element","You are stuck on an error message, receipt, form, or handwritten note and it is faster to snap a picture than transcribe it","You want feedback on a design, slide, resume, or menu and words alone cannot convey the layout","You need to convert a whiteboard sketch or flowchart photo into structured text, steps, or code"],"structure":[{"part":"1. Attach the right visual","desc":"Upload a clear, cropped image of exactly the thing you care about. A tight screenshot of one chart beats a blurry photo of a whole page. Example: crop to just the bar chart, not the entire slide."},{"part":"2. Say precisely what to look at","desc":"Name the target so the model does not guess. Example: 'Read the blue bars only' or 'Focus on the total row at the bottom, ignore the header logo.'"},{"part":"3. State what to ignore","desc":"Tell it what to skip so it does not clutter the answer with irrelevant detail. Example: 'Skip the footnotes and the legend' or 'Ignore any decorative icons.'"},{"part":"4. Specify the exact output format","desc":"Define the shape you want back so it is instantly usable. Example: 'Return a Markdown table with columns Month and Revenue, numbers only, no currency symbols.'"}],"template":"[Attach your image / screenshot / chart here]\n\nLook at the attached [image type: chart / screenshot / photo / diagram].\n\nWhat to focus on: [the specific part — e.g. \"the line for 2024 only\", \"the main navigation bar\", \"the total column\"].\n\nWhat to ignore: [anything irrelevant — e.g. \"the legend, footnotes, and background logo\"].\n\nWhat I want you to do: [the task — e.g. \"extract every value\", \"describe the layout step by step\", \"list each button and what it does\"].\n\nOutput format: [exact shape — e.g. \"a Markdown table with columns X and Y\", \"a numbered list\", \"plain sentences, no headers\"]. If a value is unclear or unreadable, mark it [uncertain] instead of guessing.","example":{"scenario":"A marketer screenshots a revenue bar chart from a PDF report and needs the numbers in a spreadsheet.","prompt":"[Attaches a screenshot of a quarterly bar chart]\n\nLook at the attached bar chart of monthly revenue.\n\nFocus on: the height of each blue bar and its month label on the x-axis.\nIgnore: the chart title, the gridlines, and the small percentage labels above the bars.\n\nExtract the revenue figure for every month shown. Output a Markdown table with two columns, Month and Revenue. Give revenue as a plain number with no dollar sign or commas. If a bar's value is not printed and you have to estimate from the axis, add [est] after that number.","output":"| Month | Revenue |\n|-------|---------|\n| Jan | 42000 |\n| Feb | 45000 |\n| Mar | 51000 |\n| Apr | 48000 [est] |\n| May | 60000 |","note":"Naming what to ignore and demanding a clean number format means the table pastes straight into a spreadsheet with zero cleanup."},"whyItWorks":"The model can see the image, but it still has to decide what matters and what shape the answer should take. When you name the target, the exclusions, and the output format, you remove all that guessing, so the AI spends its effort reading the pixels instead of inventing an interpretation. A tight, structured request also keeps the response short and directly usable, which saves you a round of \"no, I meant the other chart\" follow-ups.","tips":["Crop before you upload. A tight image of just the relevant chart or screen gets far more accurate reading than a full-page photo where your target is tiny.","Always demand a machine-friendly format for data: 'Markdown table, numbers only, no symbols' makes the result paste cleanly into Excel or Google Sheets.","Tell it how to handle uncertainty: add 'mark anything unreadable as [uncertain] rather than guessing' so you can trust the numbers you get.","For layouts, ask it to go 'top to bottom, left to right' so the description follows the visual order instead of jumping around.","Verify the important numbers against the source image yourself. Image reading is strong but not perfect, especially on dense charts, small fonts, or low-resolution screenshots."]}];
